  • Mona S.
    Chicago, IL
    63
    6
    8/16/2022

    Came to Girl & the Goat for the first time a week ago with my Husband and had a great time! Our expectations were super high as I'd been hearing about this restaurant for years.

    When we first came in the host tried to seat us at a tinny table sandwiched between two sets of couples on each side, all sharing one long bench.

    I asked if there was anything else and we ended up sharing a large table with another group that was already eating.

    I found this a little strange given the exclusivity of the reservation process and that the entire front part of the restaurant is taken up by an enormous sectional couch which they called "the lounge." Why do you need a lounge if you can't comfortably seat your reservations?

    The food, drinks, and service however, were fantastic. Our server was super friendly and engaging! For 2 people, 5 dishes is plenty (which is what our server said). 4 if you're getting the pork shank, which you absolutely should.

    Everything was super creative with innovative flavor combinations. I also loved that the restaurant is tapas style (although the plates were much bigger than traditional tapas), because it allows you to try more of the menu without breaking the bank.

    Don't skip: the pork shank, the green beans, the olive bread with feta

    The Girl and The Goat was on my "Must Try" list since I arrived in Chicago January 16th of this year.
    I mean just the Hype alone is enough to tweak anyone's curiosity. It certainly tweaked mine. Along with the month in advance reservation and the mystic uproar surrounding this establishment, I finally set foot onto this sacred ground last night.
    As my wife and I walked in, the noise level hit me like a brick. I couldn't even hear my tinnitus (ringing in my ears) I've had for decades.
    At this point, I almost did an about face to Nix this dinner. I didn't, and I'm glad I didn't.
    First off, the well trained staff of people working here keep this place running like a Swiss clock - Perfectly!

    Their menu didn't read sensationally and I found it hard to curate a comprehensive meal. That's where (again) Goats remarkable staff came to the rescue.
    We were recommended:
    *A rather delicious cocktail called - The One With The Carrots - with El Guel Mezcal, Amaro Montenegro, carrot juice and ginger. It was amazing and it was just the precursor to what was coming next!
    *Goats version of a shrimp salad - beyond good. So inventive; I loved this presentation
    *Wood Oven Roasted Pig Face with a Sunny side egg, tamarind, cilantro, red wine-maple, potato stix - best pork dish I've had in eons
    *A Halibut dish done with so much love, you could taste it. BTW, love really tastes good
    *Green Beans with Fish sauce vinaigrette and cashews - finger licking good
    *Honey-Soy Glazed Brussels Sprouts which had rosemary crema, marcona almond, togarashi

    The above wasn't a dinner, it was a feast!

    Ok, so let me break this down:
    Great service
    Incredible food
    Helpful staff
    So loud I couldn't hear my tinnitus
    And for the quality and quantity of food coming at you, Goat wasn't expensive at all.
    For once, finally, a restaurant far exceeded its hype!
    Bravo, Girl and The Goat!

  • Sophia B.
    Elite 2022
    Chicago, IL

    34
    58
    8/10/2022
    8 photos

    One of the best meals I've had in Chicago. The restaurant is beautifully decorated with large wooden beams, open windows, an outdoor eating area, and an open view of the kitchen. Our server Emily was fantastic. She was very helpful in deciding how many items we should order since the menu is family style, and she provided prompt, friendly service. The busers are also incredibly quick with changing plates for each dish and refilling water. The dishes we ordered were to die for. The tomato and stone fruit salad had a lovely spoonful of crispy quinoa on top mixed with the sesame chili vinaigrette that gave the entire salad a nice spicy crunch. The goat empanadas were fried to perfection and the smoked blueberries on the bottom gave a wonderful sweetness to the entire dish.

    Our favorite dish was the roasted summer squash. The zucchini were roasted to perfection. They still had a nice crunchy bite to them yet were still slightly soft with a wonderful charr on the bottom. Mixed with the yuzu kosho and red mustard the dish had a certain complexity that left my Dad and I trying to figure out what flavors we were tasting with each bite! We thought the roasted pig face was slightly misleading but we were happy with what arrived on our table. We assumed an actual pig face was going to be served to us, but really it was just parts of the face! The pig was beautifully cooked, and we loved the salty contrast between the pig and the red wine maple sauce. The potato sticks also added a nice crunch. The sticky glazed pork dish was the biggest plate we ordered and was incredibly filling. There was definitely an Asian flare to this-we were certain the shank had Chinese 5 spice on in it. The meat melted off the bone and was topped with something crunchy. We loved how you could make a little sandwich with the naan, different sauces, lettuce, and kimchee provided. It was a great way to end our main course, although it was a generous amount of food and we were incredibly full after. However, we weren't too full for dessert and ordered the caramel popcorn gooey butter cake. It was divine. The homemade caramel popcorn and caramel popcorn ice-cream were delicious, and we loved the cheesy butter cake with a bruleed top.

    In conclusion, if you can get a table at Girl and the Goat you must go. I think it is one of the best restaurants in the city and I am so grateful I got to spend an evening dining here.

    This place...is incredible. I know why it's such a popular and highly rated restaurant in Chicago now. Service is amazing even when it's super busy, and the food itself is so good that words can't properly express how delicious everything is. Sometimes when you go to restaurants, chefs are a bit too experimental and you have a hard time describing if you actually like a dish or not, but Girl & The Goat will be a favorite all around. No matter what you get, everything seems to hit the spot. I've been once years ago, and I remember it was a great experience, and this time was even better.

    We ordered the salmon poke, goat empanadas, goat belly, and wood oven roasted pig face. My favorites were the goat empanadas and wood oven roasted pig face. The pig face fell apart like butter, and it was the perfect amount of fattiness and richness. It wasn't so heavy that you wanted to stop eating after a few bites. The only complaint about the goat empanadas that I had was there wasn't enough. I wish I could've eaten 3 or 4 more. The salmon poke and goat belly were also really good. I actually recommend getting the salmon poke because it was refreshing and served as a nice appetizer to our heavier meat options.

    Our server was super nice and helpful the entire way through, and everyone was so attentive. I can't say enough positive things about this place. I can't wait to come back and try some of their other dishes.

    We've dined at Girl & The Goat probably close to 10 times now, if not more. I can't believe I've never reviewed it. When you see the ratings on Yelp it's clear its the best restaurant in Chicago, but its easily the best restaurant we've eaten at in any city, worldwide! The service is always outstanding and we have yet to order any dish that wasn't delicious.

    We just went a few nights ago for our five year wedding anniversary. When I made the reservation on OpenTable I marked it was for our anniversary but restaurants don't always do something for you. Girl & The Goat certainly did for us! There is a two seat bar overlooking the kitchen that they sat us at. So cool watching all the delicious food being made! And then they brought us the caulilini on the house as well as our dessert, the popcorn situation. Didn't have to call to set anything up, they just did it for us. Like I said, impeccable service.

    As for the food, every time we go we order the green beans. Sounds silly for being a vegetable but they are absolutely outstanding. We also usually get the goat empanadas which are always good and this particular trip we got the chili crunch chicken and halibut. The chicken was surprisingly better than the halibut but both were great!

    Not the easiest to get a reservation, you usually have to make it a couple months out. But the food and service is next level and will want you to keep coming back!

Frequently Asked Questions about Girl & The Goat

Does Girl & The Goat take reservations?

Yes, you can make a reservation by picking a date, time, and party size.

Does Girl & The Goat have outdoor seating?

Yes, Girl & The Goat has outdoor seating.

Yes, Girl & The Goat offers both delivery and takeout.

Girl & The Goat accepts credit cards.
